Almouse 30-May-19 06:12 AM
the important detail here is that LinkLuaModifier can run anywhere, all that you're doing is assigning the name of a modifier to a code file/fragment
if you define a lua ability, it's natural to run linkluamodifier inside the ability definition, because then all the information about the ability is in the same place
for a nonlua ability there's no "natural" place, so you just want to pick somewhere that it'll fire off once and then doesn't have to be considered again

Almouse 03-Jun-19 07:48 PM
some things are directly baked into the UI - the game will always load custom_ui_manifest.xml and custom_loading_screen.xml without you doing anything
the majority of other panorama files can be loaded from there for most purposes
for communication between lua and panorama you can either use nettables or sendevent/subscriptions (edited)
Alacrity 03-Jun-19 07:53 PM
ahhh okay. so like in general, define in custom UI manifest and in lua call with CustomUI:DynamicHud_Create() ?
Keril Artemov 03-Jun-19 07:55 PM
I have never seen anyone create UI from lua actually
well not like that
but you can do that too
Almouse 03-Jun-19 07:56 PM
almost always you probably define every single ui component in custom_ui_manifest and load them from there
if you want panels that dynamically appear/disappear, you still define them on the panorama side, and then you send a lua event when it's time for it to appear
the associated javascript file for the panel subscribes to the event and appears/disappears/loads data/etc. as needed
i wouldn't recommend any of the lua UI-related builtins other than nettables and sendevent, whose job is just to send data to the panorama, and then the panorama has to decide what to do with that information

I've found a kinda circumspect solution tho
in TakeDamage() if health is 0, set health to 1, set a flag on the unit and apply a 0 damage instance from the caster
this damage instance in turn triggers another TakeDamageKillCredit() where the victim's health is set to 0 and the game credits the kill to the caster
this way the caster does not deal any damage at all

Toyoka 06-Jun-19 02:12 AM
@Deleted User your best bet is to search for the valve-made effect (open the one[s] you think are the right effect) and mess about with the control points a bit to see whether they produce the effect you want. If any of them have "position modify on ground" or "movement place on ground" functions within the particle then you're probably looking at the right effect, although I believe sometimes if those two functions are coupled with some other functions (ie. position modify offset random with some offets) they won't show their effect properly in the editor, so you might have to mess around with disabling some things to make the effect show properly. -- kill dropped items and local items = Entities:FindAllByClassnameWithin( "dota_item_drop", caster:GetOrigin(), radius ) for _,item_physical in pairs(items) do local item = item_physical:GetContainedItem() --/--/--/--/--/--/-- item_physical:Kill() item:Kill() end
